snippet.textDisplay:
I'm not an engineer, and I'm NOT being a downer here, nor am I claiming to be an expert in ANY way, but isn't this a little over-engineered? I've seen some of the DIY community projects and they're basically a mask, a pipe, and a little motor that compresses an airbag. I mean, the engineering here is remarkable, as is the UI, etc. But the ventilators are needed three weeks ago... Maybe make a simpler model just to keep those alive who need it now...? If you had many months for R&D, this would be a good approach (what you're doing now) but fancy UIs don't save lives...

Please note: I am NOT denouncing the efforts of these fine people. I'm just wondering if maybe a K.I.S.S. method might be better here in terms of speed of deployment. If there are any engineers or respiratory therapists out there that could confirm or deny my concerns, I'd appreciate it!

It has a touchscreen yes, but not any chinese touchscreen... it's a TESLA touchscreen!
As I said please do not misunderstand, it is GOOD that there are more ventilators available.
But this video is just an ad.

snippet.textDisplay:
It's a nice idea, but it's misguided without input from people who actually make ventilators for ICU - it's a nice example of a corporation suffering from the Dunning-Kruger Effect... with a slight whiff of techno-arrogance, and clear misunderstanding of human respiratory physiology & the pathophysiology of ARDS.

Anyone can make a device that 'forces air in' but for COVID-19 patients what is critical that their respiratory muscles needs to be what triggers the ventilator's inspiratory support. The ventilator then assists their effort. Patients who are 'force ventilated' have a very high mortality. You may as well just have a person squeezing a bag. The outcome will be the same.

PRVC, PCV & VCV are actually VERY BASIC ventilator modes and for a COVID-19 patient, they don't improve mortality. SIMV, PSV and similar is what you actually want. Patients NEED to be triggering the ventilator, and for that you need some very sophisticated flow sensors & software. Do that, then I'll leave a glowing review...

Disclosure: Anaesthesiologist.
